# Named Parameters Pattern

Functions with more than 2 parameters should use named parameters (object destructuring) instead of positional parameters.

## Why

- More readable function calls
- Easier to understand which argument is which
- Safer refactoring - adding/removing parameters is less error-prone
- Better IDE autocomplete support
- Parameters can be provided in any order

## Pattern

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - positional parameters
async function processProject(
  client: PgPoolClient,
  projectId: string,
  periodFrom: string,
  periodTo: string,
  warnings: string[],
): Promise<Result> {
  // ...
}

// Call site is unclear
await processProject(client, id, from, to, warnings);

// ✅ GOOD - named parameters
interface ProcessProjectParams {
  client: PgPoolClient;
  projectId: string;
  periodFrom: string;
  periodTo: string;
  warnings: string[];
}

async function processProject({
  client,
  projectId,
  periodFrom,
  periodTo,
  warnings,
}: ProcessProjectParams): Promise<Result> {
  // ...
}

// Call site is self-documenting
await processProject({
  client,
  projectId: id,
  periodFrom: from,
  periodTo: to,
  warnings,
});
```

## When to Apply

- **Use named params**: Functions with 3+ parameters
- **Keep positional**: Functions with 1-2 parameters (e.g., `getById(client, id)`)
- **Export interfaces**: Export param interfaces for public functions so callers can use them
